within normal limits. There are no significant findings on physical examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Recommend in vitro fertilisation","Recommend progesterone supplementation","Reassure and advise to try again","Screen for antiphospholipid antibodies","Refer for genetic counselling"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s history of three consecutive miscarriages, particularly occurring after 10 weeks of gestation, raises suspicion for antiphospholipid syndrome (APS). APS is an autoimmune disorder characterised by the presence of antiphospholipid antibodies and is associated with recurrent pregnancy loss, particularly in the late first and second trimesters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreen for antiphospholipid antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This typically includes testing for lupus anticoagulant, anticardiolipin antibodies, and anti-\u03b22 glycoprotein I antibodies. If positive, these tests should be repeated after 12 weeks to confirm the diagnosis of APS. Early diagnosis is crucial as treatment with low-dose aspirin and heparin can significantly improve pregnancy outcomes in women with APS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassure and advise to try again\u003C/strong\u003E without further investigation is inappropriate given the patient\u0027s history of recurrent miscarriages. This approach fails to address the potential underlying cause and may lead to further pregnancy losses.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend progesterone supplementation\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as first-line management in this case. While progesterone is sometimes used in early pregnancy for women with a history of recurrent miscarriages, it is not specifically targeted at the underlying cause suggested by this patient\u0027s history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecommend in vitro fertilisation (IVF)\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate at this stage. IVF does not address the underlying cause of recurrent miscarriages in APS and would not prevent future losses without appropriate treatment for APS if present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for genetic counselling\u003C/strong\u003E is a consideration in recurrent pregnancy loss, but it is typically more relevant in cases of earlier miscarriages (before 10 weeks). Given the timing of this patient\u0027s losses, APS is a more likely cause and should be ruled out first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, screening for antiphospholipid antibodies is the most appropriate next step for this patient. If APS is confirmed, treatment with low-dose aspirin and heparin during pregnancy can significantly improve outcomes. If APS is ruled out, further investigations such as genetic counselling or evaluation for other causes of recurrent pregnancy loss may be considered.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Antiphospholipid syndrome is associated with recurrent pregnancy loss, particularly after 10 weeks gestation.","Diagnosis of antiphospholipid syndrome requires both clinical and laboratory criteria.","Treatment with low-dose aspirin and heparin can improve pregnancy outcomes in women with antiphospholipid syndrome."],"references":["Regan L, Rai R, Saravelos S, Li TC. Recurrent miscarriage. Green-top Guideline No. 17. BJOG. 2023 Jun 19. doi: 10.1111/1471-0528.17515."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39922"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14302"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39922"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-04T17:09:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-04T17:11:16+09:30"},"relationships":{